<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-836-636  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 836 636.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Educational Technology  August 1990 v30 n8 p18(8).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Instructional technology in education? Whither its future?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Galbraith, P.L.; Grice, R.D.; Carss, M.C.; Endean, L.; Warry, M.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A report on the future of educational technologies in Australiastresses these points: successful application of technologydepends upon its management; the teacher's role is most affectedby new technologies; teachers need facilitating factors tointerface with the technology; there will be a degree ofresistance by teachers to the new technology; changes will makesome teaching tasks unnecessary, but will create new teachingtasks.andP;  One of the greatest obstacles to implementation of newtechnology is a lack of experienced practitioners that can providehigh-level leadership.andP;  Teachers will continue in their centralrole in the educational process.andP;  Some familiar paper-basedresources will remain the most important technology.andP;  Educationaladministrators should consult practitioners and experts in orderto select a limited set of computer-based technologies fordevelopment.andP;  Microcomputers, computer-assisted instruction anddatabases are the preferred technologies.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     EducationEducational AdministrationNew TechniqueComputer-Assisted InstructionFuture Technologies.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   First consolidated delphi responses. (table)Importance ratings of technologies. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>